WHAT IS THE VL PAIR?
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  A vector-like pair (3,2,1/6) consists of:
    L component: one Weyl in (3,2,1/6)
    R component: one Weyl in (3*,2*,-1/6)
  Together they form one Dirac fermion.

  The SM generation has 5 Weyl fermions per generation.
  The VL pair has 2 Weyl fermions (= 1 Dirac).

  The correct shift for the VL pair is Convention B
  (Dirac), which is 2x Convention A (Weyl).

  The library uses Convention C, which matches Weyl
  for b_1 and b_2 but gives HALF Weyl for b_3.
  This is neither Weyl nor Dirac — it is a hybrid.

THE SESSION 3 QUESTION
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  The gap ratio 38/27 was verified in sin2_theta_w_1.py
  (9/9 checks). That script used the library values
  (1/15, 1, 1/3) to compute modified betas and the
  gap ratio. It then compared against the MEASURED
  coupling ratio from alpha_EM, sin2_tW, alpha_s.

  The gap ratio is a LEVEL 1 quantity: it depends only
  on the betas. The measured gap ratio is DERIVED from
  Level 2 couplings. They are compared, not equated.
  The 9/9 checks verified that the computation is
  internally consistent, not that Db_3 = 1/3 is the
  physically correct shift for a VL (3,2,1/6) pair.

  The unification_test.py (6/6) used the library betas
  for one-loop running above M_VL and SM betas below.
  If Db_3 should be 2/3 or 4/3 instead of 1/3, the
  unification scan results change significantly.

RESOLUTION PATH
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  The normalization must be resolved by an external
  reference that explicitly lists the one-loop beta
  shift for a VL (3,2,1/6) doublet in GUT normalization.

  Candidates:
    - Kowalska & Kumar, JHEP 12 (2019) 094
    - Bhattacherjee et al., JHEP 05 (2018) 090
    - Dermisek, Phys. Rev. D 87 (2013) 055008
  These papers enumerate VL representations and their
  beta shifts. A table entry for (3,2,1/6) settles it.

  Until resolved, all three gap ratios should be tracked:
    38/27 (library, Db_3=1/3)
    19/12 (Weyl, Db_3=2/3)
    6/5   (Dirac, Db_3=4/3)

